body:
Right now, when you add something with a required onPressed argument, and then tell the IDE to add all the required arguments, we add onPressed with the default value `null`.

It would be super helpful if instead of defaulting to null, it defaulted to a lambda with the given arguments but an empty body, as in:

```dart
  onPressed: () { },
```

cc @abarth

comment_data.body: This sounds similar to work that @pq is doing for auto-complete and `child:` / `children:` args.

> Am I right that in general the `onPressed` property is a `VoidCallback`?

Yes.

> Any exceptions?

ExpandIcon.onPressed takes a bool argument.

> Besides the presence of an `onPressed` required arg, any other triggers?
> Maybe we should do this for all args that take callbacks?

I think it would make sense to automatically provide an empty lambda with the right types and argument names whenever you automatically add an argument that has a typedef, yes.

onPressed is special only because it's @required.
Do we want to add the type of arguments when expanding in this way? It helps document what it is you're receiving...

> Do we want to add the type of arguments when expanding in this way? It helps document what it is you're receiving...

If that's idiomatic, sure.  (Though a general rule for the analyzer has been to add as little as possible.)

To be clear, you mean:

    onPressed: (boolean value) { }

?
Whether it's idiomatic is an interesting question, but yes, that's what I meant.

title: onPressed autocomplete
